Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.19,0:00:46.23,Default,,0,0,0,,So\Ngive
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.23,0:00:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The trouble with focusing on the beauty\Nof everything
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.00,0:00:55.52,Default,,0,0,0,,>> is that you get stoned out all the time.\NIt's very hard to get past these
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.52,0:00:59.28,Default,,0,0,0,,flowers. I purposely avoid looking at\Nthese flowers
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.28,0:01:05.19,Default,,0,0,0,,cuz they are so it makes you break out\Nin tears. You know
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.19,0:01:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,how beautiful music makes you break out\Nin tears.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.24,0:01:18.79,Default,,0,0,0,,You can't prove the aesthetic\Nexquisite joy
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.79,0:01:27.36,Default,,0,0,0,,that you experience out of beauty.\NIt's not within the linear domain.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.36,0:01:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. Where was I?\NI got talking about beauty and you see
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.92,0:01:43.75,Default,,0,0,0,,it happens. I'm not going to look at\Nbeauty anymore.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.75,0:01:48.32,Default,,0,0,0,,It has a positive effect, you know, on\Nyour neuronal connections.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.32,0:01:54.96,Default,,0,0,0,,The uh the best uh preparation for your\Nchildren is a spiritual religious uh
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.96,0:02:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,experiences as a child and u aesthetic\Nbeauty, beautiful music
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.36,0:02:09.52,Default,,0,0,0,,uh an appreciation for beauty.\NYeah. So
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.52,0:02:14.80,Default,,0,0,0,,I myself that was part of my religious\Nupbringing was
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.80,0:02:19.68,Default,,0,0,0,,a constant exposure to beauty. Both my\Nparents were musicians
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.68,0:02:26.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and uh I was a member of the art\Ninstitute and I played violin and piano
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.08,0:02:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and I was a soloist, a boy soprano\Nand I remember being in a Greek
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.00,0:02:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,cathedral\Nand I sang the uh obligato
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.36,0:02:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,over Angelus\Nin this soprano voice. I had a high
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.84,0:02:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,soprano.\NSo there you are in the Greek cathedral,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.20,0:02:51.51,Default,,0,0,0,,stained glass windows.\NSunlight is coming in and lighting up
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.51,0:02:56.48,Default,,0,0,0,,the clouds of incense.\NA full choir and a full orchestra at
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.48,0:03:01.36,Default,,0,0,0,,this cathedral.\NAnd here this voice
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.36,0:03:06.87,Default,,0,0,0,,came through me. I had the soprano\Nobligato very high obligato above the
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.87,0:03:12.95,Default,,0,0,0,,whole choir and orchestra\Nand a presence sang
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.95,0:03:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,it was a presence\Nthat sang
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.92,0:03:24.95,Default,,0,0,0,,that wipes you out. You shouldn't think\Nabout such things when you're giving a
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.95,0:03:30.48,Default,,0,0,0,,lecture.\NGo back to the next slide.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.48,0:03:33.84,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to uh we're going to put\Ntogether a book of slides. We we now
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.84,0:03:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,have about 110 of them. Every time we\Ngive a new lecture in Sedona, it creates
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.44,0:03:43.51,Default,,0,0,0,,a whole new slide. Next one we're going\Nto do on the miraculous and uh we'll
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.51,0:03:51.28,Default,,0,0,0,,talk about\Nthe miraculous.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.28,0:03:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, this looks too academic. She says\Nthat's too complicated. We'll go to the
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.28,0:04:02.31,Default,,0,0,0,,next one.\Nthe the basic people people the basic
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.31,0:04:07.04,Default,,0,0,0,,just being decent decent human being. Uh\Nwhat do you have to do to evolve
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.04,0:04:11.28,Default,,0,0,0,,spiritually?\NUh I say the best thing to do is to be
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.28,0:04:14.87,Default,,0,0,0,,kind to all of life and all of its\Nexpressions.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.87,0:04:21.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Be kind to all.\NUh and a pervasive goodwill towards
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.04,0:04:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself and towards life. So goodwill\Nmeans towards your own life towards your
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.32,0:04:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,own life goodwill and appreciation for\Nits beauty and to see your own life as a
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.68,0:04:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,gift\Nthat leads to a a style of life which is
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.12,0:04:42.47,Default,,0,0,0,,contemplative.\NMeditation uh has its place and I spent
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.47,0:04:47.60,Default,,0,0,0,,many years medit meditating on a regular\Nbasis.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.60,0:04:52.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Contemplation\Nis putting into practice spiritual
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.32,0:04:56.56,Default,,0,0,0,,principles\Nto such an extent that you eventually
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.56,0:05:03.68,Default,,0,0,0,,become that. It's not something you do.\NIt's what you are. What you are is
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.68,0:05:07.75,Default,,0,0,0,,loving and gentle and supportive and\Nexquisite.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.75,0:05:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why every we all cried this\Nmorning. Everybody I was greeting. I
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.24,0:05:15.75,Default,,0,0,0,,just went into a state of joy. They went\Ninto a state of joy. We both are crying.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.75,0:05:23.68,Default,,0,0,0,,It's hard to get through a whole crowd.\NYou know what I'm saying?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.68,0:05:27.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone was just being the reality of\Ntheir essence. That's all they were
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.44,0:05:32.88,Default,,0,0,0,,doing. You know, just being what they\Nactually are. And uh safety is when you
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.88,0:05:42.40,Default,,0,0,0,,can just be uh what you really are.\NSo these things may not be
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.40,0:05:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,acceptable in the modern post soal\Npostmodern world.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.19,0:05:53.52,Default,,0,0,0,,But these are these were what I grew up\Nin in uh middle America and Wisconsin
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.52,0:06:02.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and 1930s around in there 20s.\NUh I thought everybody was like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.88,0:06:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,To me there was only two kinds of people\Nin the world. There were people who were
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.00,0:06:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,decent, honest, pleasant, respectable,\Netc.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.00,0:06:20.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh, and then there were gangsters,\NMachine Gun Kelly and Babyface Nelson
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.08,0:06:27.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and and the mafia guys in Chicago,\Nliquor guys, I forget what their name,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.19,0:06:31.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Scarface.\NAnd then there were then then there was
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.03,0:06:36.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the people that that everybody was\Ndependable. They tried to get there on
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.40,0:06:41.52,Default,,0,0,0,,time. They tried to be responsible for\Ntheir own emotions and not pour them all
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.52,0:06:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,over you. Everybody tried to be neat and\Nfair and ethical and and uh humane
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.84,0:06:53.36,Default,,0,0,0,,towards the animals and everybody else.\NEverybody was gracious towards uh
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.36,0:06:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,everybody else. Everybody tried to be\Nmodest, diplomatic, polite, firm and
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.56,0:07:02.08,Default,,0,0,0,,nice.\NUh
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.08,0:07:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,but what you can see when we calibrated\Nthe level of consciousness of mankind
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.56,0:07:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,what what what I consider to be the norm\Nis frankly the exception.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.68,0:07:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh being sold to the earth is now sort\Nof I guess exceptional to be easygoing
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.80,0:07:26.31,Default,,0,0,0,,to let people off the hook. I know you\Ngot them on the hook, so why not let
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.31,0:07:31.28,Default,,0,0,0,,them off the hook? You know, why not let\Npeople off the hook and forgive them
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.28,0:07:35.36,Default,,0,0,0,,because\Nuh people just don't know any better.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.36,0:07:42.63,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, so let's move on.\NUm this is the to clarify what the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.63,0:07:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,what's going on in mind. Your mind is\N99% silent.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.59,0:07:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,99% of your mind is silent. 1% is what\Nyou're listening to.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.28,0:08:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,If you look underneath thought, you'll\Nsee that underneath the thinkingness,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.40,0:08:05.75,Default,,0,0,0,,which is the noise going on in your\Nmind, there is an infinite stillness, an
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.75,0:08:13.28,Default,,0,0,0,,infinite profound stillness and silence.\NThat's 99% of your mind is silent. So
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.28,0:08:17.03,Default,,0,0,0,,instead of bemoning the fact that you\Ncan't seem to get your mind to stop
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.03,0:08:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,thinking,\Nwhat I advise people to do is stop
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.96,0:08:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,trying to don't try to get your mind to\Nstop. Instead, look beneath the mind and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.12,0:08:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll see that beneath the mind is an\Ninfinite field of silence.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.52,0:08:35.27,Default,,0,0,0,,If it were not for the infinite field of\Nsilence, you wouldn't know what you were
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.27,0:08:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,thinking.\NThe television set is blank. If it
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.80,0:08:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,wasn't when you turn it on, it goes it\Nlights up.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.88,0:08:49.76,Default,,0,0,0,,If it So, if it wasn't for the field,\Nyou wouldn't know what you're seeing on
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.76,0:08:56.39,Default,,0,0,0,,the set. So, your mind is like\N99% silent.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.39,0:09:00.39,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like the noise. It's like walking\Nthrough the woods.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.39,0:09:04.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The woods is actually silent. And the\Nfact that you hear a bird, the reason
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.88,0:09:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,you hear the bird is be not because of\Nthe song of the bird, but because of the
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.04,0:09:13.44,Default,,0,0,0,,silence. If it weren't for the silence,\Nyou couldn't hear the bird. Is that
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.44,0:09:17.44,Default,,0,0,0,,correct? It went for the fact that your\Nmind is intrinsically silent, you
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.44,0:09:22.95,Default,,0,0,0,,wouldn't know what you're thinking. So\Nlook and become at one with the silence,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.95,0:09:28.48,Default,,0,0,0,,the infinite nonlinear silence. And\Nthat's part of be your life becoming a
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.48,0:09:31.92,Default,,0,0,0,,prayer.\NYou see, the mind is always busy. Look
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.92,0:09:36.95,Default,,0,0,0,,what it's doing here all the time. All\Nyou have to do is turn on everybody's
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.95,0:09:42.48,Default,,0,0,0,,turn on any night's television.\NThere's a contest. There's a big contest
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.48,0:09:47.44,Default,,0,0,0,,amongst the victims. Who can be the\Nbiggest victim? There's two contests.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.44,0:09:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,One is to be the world's biggest victim\Nand get the greatest sympathy.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.80,0:10:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,And the other is to be right.\Npeople will do anything to be right.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.08,0:10:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, so this is what the mind is doing\Nto keep itself busy. And uh we said what
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.88,0:10:10.39,Default,,0,0,0,,keeps a thing going is the juice you're\Ngetting off of it. So the way to
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.39,0:10:14.48,Default,,0,0,0,,disconnect the mind is to look and see\Nwhat kind of juice you're getting out of
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.48,0:10:19.44,Default,,0,0,0,,these thoughts, memories, etc. You don't\Nhave to give up the thoughts. You have
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.44,0:10:23.27,Default,,0,0,0,,to only give up the juice that you're\Ngetting off of it. The same as hate or
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.27,0:10:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,any other thing that you don't want to\Nhave. You say, "Am I willing?" You don't
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.92,0:10:32.72,Default,,0,0,0,,have to be willing to give up hatred.\NThat's not possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.72,0:10:38.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Hatred pays off so good in our current\Nworld. You can't live without it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.80,0:10:43.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But we willing to give up the juice that\Nyou're getting out of the hatred. So
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.12,0:10:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,once you give up the juice of\Nresentment, self-pity, guilt, you
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.68,0:10:52.72,Default,,0,0,0,,realize how narcissistic guilt is\Nwalling around. Oh me, oh bad me, why
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.72,0:10:56.80,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm so awful. Oh, sackloth and ashes. Oh\Npenance.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.80,0:11:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, how narcissistic it is. Don't\Nyou see? You're not doing this for God.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.92,0:11:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, penance for God, sackcloth, and\Nashes. Oh, woe is me.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.88,0:11:15.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, why would God be happier that\Nunless he was a sadist of some kind,
